    ## Theoretical Results on Polylogarithmic Algorithms
    
    Algorithms exist that compute the nth prime in time polynomial in the input length (m), which means polylogarithmic in the prime value itself, i.e., time polylog(p_n). 
    
    Known unconditional deterministic algorithms achieving time polynomial in the input length rely on heavy number-theoretic subroutines, with the precise best published bound being near-linear in the output size, expressed as O(M(log p_n) log p_n).
    
    ## Practical Implementation
    
    In practice, for relatively small inputs below 1 million, algorithms sieve over a range containing the nth prime; for larger values, they use a low-biased estimate via the inverse logarithmic integral and fast prime counting. Computing the 10^12th prime takes about 1 second, the 10^13th prime takes under 10 seconds, and the 10^14th prime takes under 30 seconds.
    
    The search results do not contain specific research developments from 2025-2026 on exact polylogarithmic algorithms for nth prime computation. The theoretical foundations showing such algorithms exist are well-established, but recent advances in this specific area were not found in the search results.
    
    
