    Based on the web search results, here are the key findings related to étale cohomology, algebraic geometry, and fast algorithms for counting points in 2025:
    
    ## Computation of Étale Cohomology
    
    A key result is the computation of étale cohomology on curves in single exponential time. For a smooth connected curve X over a field k with a finite locally constant sheaf, an algorithm computes the first étale cohomology with complexity exponential in n log n and the arithmetic genus of the normal completion.
    
    ## Counting Points on Curves
    
    An algorithm for counting points on hyperelliptic curves over a finite field of odd characteristic uses Monsky-Washnitzer cohomology to compute a p-adic approximation to the characteristic polynomial of Frobenius, with asymptotic running time O(g^{4+ε} n^{3+ε}) for a curve of genus g over the field of p^n elements.
    
    ## Recent Developments in Higher-Dimensional Varieties
    
    Recent implementations feature GPU-optimized linear algebra and achieve state-of-the-art performance on quintic curves and zeta functions of cubic fourfolds, with systematic computations of zeta functions of quintic surfaces.
    
    ## Applications and Theory
    
    Étale cohomology was introduced by Alexander Grothendieck in the 1960s, and the Weil Conjectures, proved by Grothendieck and Pierre Deligne, demonstrate the deep connection between étale cohomology and number theory.
    
    
